{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17605192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17605192"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:02:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:02:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15865"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15865"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.17,0,0.75,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8556"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72410"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8556"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15865"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57880"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8679"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20524"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20527"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72410"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe indifferent gonad forms from intermediate mesoderm and underlying mesenchyme along the genital ridge. This bipotential structure can develop into either male or female reproductive organs depending on genetic factors.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the embryological origin of the indifferent gonad?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Neural crest cells","Lateral plate mesoderm","Surface ectoderm","Intermediate mesoderm","Endoderm"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe indifferent gonad develops from \u003Cstrong\u003Eintermediate mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E and coelomic epithelium along the genital ridge. This occurs around week six of development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeural crest cells\u003C/strong\u003E contribute to the autonomic nervous system and adrenal medulla\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral plate mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms the body wall and limb components\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurface ectoderm\u003C/strong\u003E gives rise to epidermis and its derivatives\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms the epithelial lining of the digestive and respiratory tracts\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe intermediate mesoderm also gives rise to the urinary system, demonstrating the close developmental relationship between the urinary and reproductive systems.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The indifferent gonad develops into either testes or ovaries depending on presence of SRY gene on Y chromosome.","The indifferent gonad forms from intermediate mesoderm and genital ridge by week six of development.","Both male and female gonads share common embryological origins before sexual differentiation."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","Rey R, Josso N, Racine C. Sexual Differentiation. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Blackman MR, et al., editors. Endotext [Internet]. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com, Inc. [Updated 2020 May 27]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK279001/#"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions